Q2 which place better to build sofa, bridge for Paola, engine room for Raluca or other place for someone
Q3 does throwing a grenade to mush in a room with human count as playing against your team?
On december 17, 2013
[6826491]

A2: The Bridge is the ideal place for the first Sofa, especially if Paola has Logistics. This keeps her at her station, and she can always use either of the front turrets if the need arises. If there is a second Sofa BP and a Lizaro Jungle BP, you can build a second Sofa (typically in the Lab, so both Chun and Finola have access to one.) And if Chun has Lethargy, the Sofa in the Lab will HIGHLY pay off for your crew.

The reason to not place it in the Engine Room is a simple one: Pilgred is important, but the proximity to the Dorms means that people will be able to relay with Raluca easily enough. Additionally, you don't want to finish Pilgred before the Mush are dealt with, and risk handing them an easy Mush victory.

A3: If there's zero doubt that the Mush is in that room, probably not, unless you manage to kill one of the human players in the process.
On december 17, 2013
TradeFederation
MoxrexQ2 which place better to build sofa, bridge for Paola, engine room for Raluca or other place for someone
Q3 does throwing a grenade to mush in a room with human count as playing against your team?

A2 : Usually the sofa should go with the most active and or skilled player, Paola or Raluca. Most ships like the bridge, because you have to be there to scan/decode signals/launch the ship, and Paola's logistics skill can let two people basically get the benefit of using the same sofa. If Raluca is your only tech, or the Plasma Shield is up in Nexus, getting her more AP can be a good idea for getting these critical items MUCH faster.

A3 : Humans using the Grenade on the ship is fine and justifiable, but its also usually not helpful, as its collateral damage can be pretty severe. I usually keep it locked in BIOS. It works much better on expo's though, where too much POWER is never enough, and there is no blowback

q38 Why on one of My end game screens I can`t see players names (only characters) and those cute hearts counters, of which You give If someones play was fine to You? I know this ship is already over.
On december 19, 2013
[6826491]

A38: To see those, one of two things needs to happen before you can see the names, whichever of these two comes first.

Either:

1. Everyone needs to confirm their end (after a final jump, the destruction of the ship, or an early death.)

2. A week needs to pass since the very last cycle of the ship.

Once either condition is met, you can then see the names and hearts.

Q90 What are the consequences of a fuel tank break?

On december 23, 2013
[6826491]

A90: Contrary to what some players may think, a broken fuel tank does not leak fuel. It only blocks access to the tank, so you can't extract or inject fuel. They break so often, it makes much more sense to only repair one of them right before you need to extract fuel...because it will probably be broken again next cycle. It's a tremendous AP sink on newbie-filled ships.

As for the other question: If you're doing the thing with a Mush who has at least one spore, you may get spored by them. This is why Chun is the only "safe" character to do the thing with, if you're a male character. I've not heard of any diseases that can be transmitted by DTT, though.

[7971963]

A98 - Yes.

More detailed answer

Ships generally have different levels of "Victory" accepted by the community.

Draw: The Daedalus is destroyed without Mush involvement. (Mush are dead or inactive)

Mush Victory
Minor - The Daedalus is destroyed by the Mush
Normal - The Daedalus arrives at Sol with Mush on-board.
Greater - The Daedalus arrives at Eden with Mush on-board
+1 - The Mush have destroyed Humanity's last hope. (Chun)

Human Victory
Normal - The Daedalus arrives at Sol without Mush.
Greater - The Daedalus arrives at Eden without Mush.
+1 - The Humans have researched the Serum.

The Research (which requires a dead Mush) is what matters, not the item itself.

A135 followup - 'general crew', those whose skills are not urgently needed for specific tasks, are vital.

These are the players who 'do what needs doing'. Resetting research, projects, and pilgred for the specialists, moving equipment around, bringing meals to the specialists who most need to conserve points (Paola comes to mind), repairs if needed, fighting fires, (finding fires and broken equipment, for that matter!), freezing the alien steaks from the last expo, helping tend plants if that's needed, helping find a good planet if that's needed, doing it with those needing morale, opening any space capsules, loading fuel...

Basically everything that a specialist doesn't only do (like piloting or comms terminal). As the game progresses, the random number generator gets meaner. More and more things go wrong and have to be fixed - and all that's generalist level work, especially when there's so much to repair/extinguish/shoot that there's no way for those best at it to get it all done.

westas1Q238 who has to be leveld up firstly, so that when I play that charachter I have his best skill at hand? I am a bronze player, but quite interested about silver too plays! Thanks!

A238
For bronze:
Roland should always have Pilot (his level 2). It's just more useful than Sprinter (his level 1), and you can't rely on anyone but Roland and Hua to have it (though some others have it as a higher level skill).
Gioele should probably have Paranoid (his level 2) since he's the only one with that skill. It gives 2 cameras, and having 5 cameras instead of 3 is useful, especially on active ships with a sofa.
Example camera locations:
Alpha Dorm (beds)
Bravo Dorm (beds)
Medlab (bed)
Bridge (sofa for Comms Officer)
Engine Room (Raluca)
This lets everyone safely go offline, and use all the beds. It also lets Raluca stay in her own room, though she won't get bed AP.
Note: If you end up Mush, this skill will work against you, but Solid (his level 1) doesn't work for Mush anyway.
Terrence should usually at least be level 2 for Technician. However, a better bronze strategy might be to have him level 3. Pick Technician (his level 2) if there are no other technicians. If there is a tech, but not enough pilots, pick Pilot (his level 3). If there's a tech and plenty of pilots you might even pick Robotics Expert (his level 1).
Finola's Medic (her level 2) is about the same as Biologist (her level 1), with the research bonus and ability to see pill properties, but also lets her heal more HP at a time and "carry out operations", which I assume means surgery to fix wounds. It's not necessary to the ship to be level 2 but it might be more helpful, and all you lose is a bonus on two NERON projects.

That's about all I can see, most characters need their level 1 skill.

- Ian extracts a spore, alone, with no cameras. Eleesha enters the room 2 cycles later. She can't make the action visible, even if she enters the room 10 or 100 times in a row.
- Ian extracts a spore in front of a camera. The action is made visible by the camera. If Eleesha enters the room later, she can "notice" the action. Sometimes she can stay in the room for a while, and then she does an action, or she refreshes the page, or someone else does something, and it triggers the skill.

Taking the skill at the beginning of the game is useless. There are two ways to really use it.

If someone turns mush during the game, and is online right then (infected by ration or trapped shelf), they can choose Anonymush right away and the crew won't know there are 3 instead of 2. If the first two mush get killed and not the third, the crew may think all the mush are gone, and stop protecting themselves.

If one of the two starting mush saves one slot for Anonymush, they can later infect someone and immediately take the skill, even if the new mush is offline. This has similar results to the first one, except it's one of the starting mush that's hidden.

299 Is patrol ship hull integrity (health) is different than being actually broken? Can you check validity of my speculation, please? You can fly it no matter how badly it's damaged, but you can't if it's broken. Also when a patrol ship brakes down, this has no effect on its health. Health can only be drained during a flight. If it reaches zero - patrol ship gets destroyed, pilot dies. Drones do not fix patrol ship health, but can fix it from being broken.
On january 6, 2014
Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mÃ©chant ?

A 299

You're right. If a patrol ship is broken, you can't take off. The easiest way to repair it is to drop a drone in the bay, it will repair it for free. If someone wants to repair it, they must use scrap metal.

It can also break when you're outside the Daedalus (random event at cycle change or, as illogical as it sounds, it can be broken by a fire or an electrical spike in the bay... when it's not in the bay). In that case you can't land or fire, you must repair it yourself first.

You should also know that a broken patrol ship counts as 2 broken things in the alerts.

The hull of a patrol ship can be damaged by hunters at cycle change, and also when a non pilot takes off and lands. The Pasiphae is damaged every time you collect scrap when there are hunters, even asteroids. If you see that the hull of a ship is low, you can renovate with scrap metal. But drones can't do anything.

If the hull gets down to 0, the ship explodes and the pilot dies.

On january 8, 2014
[6826491]

A332: Impet nailed it. Your inventory is full. (Also, you might not want to mention that you have the Sabotage option...) Drop your stuff in the Rear Storage, click on the tank, extract as many fuel as you need (you can carry up to three at a time). Then in the engine room, examine the combustion chamber first, so you don't risk overfilling it. Then click on each fuel capsule, and inject them one at a time. Again, watch the fuel level, because sometimes more than one person might fill the tank at the same time. It might also take two or more trips, for some distant planets.

If you're leaving orbit, then only load one fuel. If you're heading to a planet, then load exactly the amount of fuel you need. Otherwise the ship will miss the target.

A360 There's a chain of command. Paola starts the game with the comm officer rank. Fear not though - you do not need to personally decode it. Keep the ship alive and things stable enough so your Paola can do her job without AP-draining interruptions, and when that rebel base contacts your ship, she should be able to decode it easily - and you'll get your glory bonus.
